          </div>
          <div class="last-updated">Last Updated: 8 October 2025</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- What's Included -->
    <section class="included-section section">
      <div class="container-wide">
        <div class="section-header">
          <h2>What's Included in Our Auction Representation Service?</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">Remove the emotion and stress from auction day with professional representation. We've attended hundreds of auctions across Queensland and execute strategic bidding plans designed to secure your property at the best possible price, replacing emotion with strategy, experience, and discipline. Need full end-to-end support including property search? Check out our <a href="/services/full-buyers-agent-service">Full Premium Support Package</a>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="included-grid">
          <div class="included-item">
            <h3>Pre-Auction Property Analysis</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Detailed property inspection and condition assessment</li>
              <li>Independent market value analysis</li>
              <li>Comparable sales research in the area</li>
              <li>Identification of property strengths and weaknesses</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="included-item">
            <h3>Strategic Bidding Plan</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Customized bidding strategy based on market analysis</li>
              <li>Maximum bid recommendation aligned with property value</li>
              <li>Tactical approach for different auction scenarios</li>
              <li>Contingency planning for competitive bidding</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="included-item">
            <h3>Professional Auction Representation</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Experienced bidder representing you on auction day</li>
              <li>Strategic bid placement and timing</li>
              <li>Reading the room and other bidders</li>
              <li>Calm, disciplined execution of bidding strategy</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="included-item">
            <h3>Post-Auction Negotiation</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Negotiation if property is passed in</li>
              <li>Strategic follow-up with selling agent</li>
              <li>Contract review and settlement coordination</li>
              <li>Ongoing support through to settlement</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Why Professional Bidding Works -->
    <section class="why-bidding section">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <h2>The Psychology of Auction Bidding</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">Why emotion is your enemy at auctions</p>
        </div>
        <div class="psychology-grid">
          <div class="psychology-item">
            <h3>Emotional Attachment Costs Money</h3>
            <p>
              You've fallen in love with the property. You've imagined your furniture in the living room,
              your kids in the backyard. This emotional attachment makes you vulnerable to overbidding.
              A professional bidder has no emotional connection, just a strategic plan and a maximum price.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="psychology-item">
            <h3>Adrenaline Leads to Mistakes</h3>
            <p>
              Your heart is racing, palms are sweaty, and suddenly you're in a bidding war. Adrenaline
              makes you bid higher than planned. Professional bidders stay calm under pressure, executing
              the strategy without emotion clouding judgment.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="psychology-item">
            <h3>Intimidation Tactics Work</h3>
            <p>
              Other bidders use intimidation: aggressive early bids, confident body language, psychological
              games. These tactics are designed to scare off competition. Experienced bidders recognise
              these tricks and don't fall for them.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="psychology-item">
            <h3>Knowing When to Walk Away</h3>
            <p>
              The hardest part of any auction is walking away when the price exceeds the property's value.
              We've set your maximum bid based on independent analysis. If bidding goes beyond that, we stop.
              No regrets, no overpaying.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Bidding Strategies -->
    <section class="strategies-section section">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <h2>Our Auction Bidding Strategies</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="strategies-grid">
          <div class="strategy-item">
            <h3>The Late Entry</h3>
            <p>
              Sometimes the best strategy is to stay silent and let other bidders compete. We enter late
              with a strong bid when others are fatigued, often securing the property without driving up
              the price unnecessarily.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="strategy-item">
            <h3>The Confident Opener</h3>
            <p>
              A strong opening bid can intimidate other buyers and set the tone. We use this when market
              analysis suggests fewer competing bidders or when we want to establish control early.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="strategy-item">
            <h3>The Incremental Approach</h3>
            <p>
              Small, steady bid increases can frustrate aggressive bidders and make them reveal their
              maximum price. This strategy works well when we sense uncertainty in other bidders.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="strategy-item">
            <h3>The Strategic Pause</h3>
            <p>
              Deliberately pausing before bidding creates psychological pressure on other buyers. It makes
              them question whether we're still interested, often causing them to bid against themselves.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

